t’s important to understand your choices. Our cot mattress guide covers lots of important information, so once you’ve read that, it should hopefully be a little easier to make an informed choice. But first, let’s look at some of the simple considerations…</p><p><br></p><p><strong>How to choose a cot bed mattress</strong></p><p>There are a number of things to consider when looking for a cot bed mattress, these include:</p><p><br></p><p></p><ul><li>Budget</li><p></p><p></p><li>Space</li><p></p><p></p><li>Comfort</li><p></p><p></p><li>Support</li><p></p><p></p><li>Longevity</li><p></p><p></p><li>Easy cleaning</li><p></p><p></p><li>Sustainability</li></ul><p></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Budgeting for your cot bed mattress</strong></p><p>When it comes to shopping for baby, a budget is everything. While it would be great if the sky was the limit, with so much to buy, you have to make smart choices. It’s worth considering your cot mattress in your initial budget. The more you can put aside for it, the better your chances of getting a mattress that offers the right level of support and quality.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Think about your nursery size</strong></p><p>The size of your child’s nursery can affect your options for mattresses. There are a range of sizes available to suit various cots, but not all mattress types are available in all sizes.</p><p><br></p><p>If your nursery is short on space, or you’re looking to fit your child’s cot in your room, you’ll need to identify what mattresses are available in these smaller sizes. Figure out the type of cot you need – standard cot bed, mini cot bed, space saving cot, etc. then you can find the right mattress to suit it. At Ickle Bubba, we have mattresses to suit every cot size we offer.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Understanding mattress cores</strong></p><p>Comfort is a huge factor when picking a mattress. After all, you want your little one to enjoy long, cosy sleeps. But you also want to ensure that they have the proper support. The best way to look at this is to compare the various types of mattress cores. There are a range of cot mattress cores available, including:</p><p><br></p><p></p><ul><li>Fibre</li><p></p><p></p><li>Foam</li><p></p><p></p><li>Sprung</li><p></p><p></p><li>Pocket Sprung</li></ul><p></p><p><br></p><p>The different cores reflect different levels of comfort and support, along with additional factors such as sustainability and longevity.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p><strong>How long do you intend to use the mattress?</strong></p><p>This is worth considering, as some mattresses offer more longevity. Mattresses that have a dual core design have one side that’s designed to be suitable for babies, while the other has been adapted to provide maximum support for a growing toddler.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Easy cleaning mattresses</strong></p><p>Everyone knows that babies and toddlers can have occasional accidents at night – especially as they start to potty train. So, it’s always useful to find mattresses that are easy to clean. Look for whether they come with a removable and washable cover as that makes it much easier. It’s also important to look out for features such as waterproof and water resistant, as these can be a lifesaver too.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Sustainable mattresses</strong></p><p>Sustainability is an increasingly important issues, and something many of us try to factor into our shopping habits. While not every mattress core is sustainable, some such as Fibre, are often made from recyclable and organic materials, so you can shop in an eco-friendly way. Be sure to check the product information to see if this applies to your mattress of choice.</p><p><br></p></div></div></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1679417683298" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1679417683298"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1679417683315" data-id="1679417683315"><div data-label="